For zero order reaction, if concentration of reactant is $\left[\mathrm{C}_0\right]$ at time t and $\frac{\left[\mathrm{C}_0\right]}{2}$ at time $\mathrm{t}_2$, then
$\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{k}=\frac{\left[\mathrm{C}_0\right]-\left[\frac{\mathrm{C}_0}{2}\right]}{\mathrm{t}_2-\mathrm{t}_1}=\frac{\left[\mathrm{C}_0\right]-\left[\frac{\mathrm{C}_0}{2}\right]}{\mathrm{t}_{1 / 2}} \\
\therefore \quad & \mathrm{t}_{1 / 2}=\frac{\left[\mathrm{C}_0\right]}{2 \mathrm{k}}
\end{aligned}$
Thus, $\mathrm{t}_{1 / 2}$ for zero order reaction is directly proportional to the initial concentration of the reactant.

Carius method is used to find halogen in an organic compound. Here, the weighed amount of organic compound is heated in a sealed tube with fuming $\mathrm{HNO}_3$ in the presence of $\mathrm{AgNO}_3$. As a result, halogen present in organic compound is converted into Agx which is weighed. The percentage of halogens can be calculated with the help of direct formula as
$\begin{aligned}
\% \text { of chlorine } & =\frac{35.5}{143.5} \times \frac{\text { weight of } \mathrm{AgCl} \times 100}{\text { weight of compound }} \\
\% \text { of bromine } & =\frac{80}{188} \times \frac{\text { weight of } \mathrm{AgBr} \times 100}{\text { weight of compound }} \\
\% \text { of iodine } & =\frac{127}{235} \times \frac{\text { weight of } \mathrm{AgI} \times 100}{\text { weight of compound }}
\end{aligned}$

